.CENTER
INTRODUCTION
.skip 1
     This Documentation Guide is a collection of standards, procedures, models
and documentation aids for achieveing consistency and high quality in all formal
documentation produced by the Technical Division.
.paragraph
     It applies to all Division personnel who are involved, however remotely, with
 producing formal documentation. Formal documentation is any descriptive
and structured write-up of software or hardware, other than that
created for very limited use, appearing either on a computer system or in a 
conventional publication. It is normally produced as a direct result of the 
development and release of Tymshare software or hardware, and is for use within the
Company. This formal documentation is referred to in the following sections of this
guide as "documentation" or "documents".
.paragraph
     All formal documentation such as manuals, handbooks and user guides will be
produced in accordance with this guide. Digressions from this guide can be allowed
to satisfy exceptional user requirements, but anyone who wishes to digress from this
guide must be prepared to justify his digression to the Quality Assurance
Technical Writer.
.paragraph
     Other formal documentation such as specifi cations, proposals or reports 
should be produced in accordance with this guide when appropriate. The Quality
Assurance Technical Writer maintains a collection of various document models
for specifications, proposals and reports. He will furnish such models to any
person who wishes to use them in writing his own specification, proposal or 
report.
.page
.center
SECTION 1
.skip 1
.center
RESPONSIBILITIES
.skip 1
1.1  GENERAL
.skip 1
.paragraph
     A document goes through three major phases from the time it is first thought
of to the time it is finally delivered. These three phases are preparation and
submittal, review and approval, and production, in that order.
.skip 1
.paragraph
     Responsibility for these phases is spread over several different areas of the
Technical Division. This section explains who is responsible for what in each
phase, while section 2  explains the steps within each phase, and section 3 
establishes standards to be followed when producing documents covered by 
this guide.
.skip 1
.paragraph
     Documentation in the Technical Division occurs in two ways: a programmer 
generates it, or the Quality Assurance Technical Writer generates it. In this
document "writer" always means the Quality Assurance Technical Writer.
.skip  2
1.200pROGRAMMER
.skip 1
.paragraph
     Whether a document is generated by a programmer or the writer, the programmer's
foremost concern is technical accuracy and completeness of coverage. He is
depended on to provide accurate technical information, not to compose or to edit.
When he has prepared his document in accordance with paragraph 2.4 of this
guide, he submits it to the writer. At this point primary responsibility for the
document is assumed by the writer, although the programmer is still responsible
for technical content.
.skip 1
.paragrap

     A programmer is responsible also for reviewing and approving any document 
sent to him for review and approval. He should make any changes necessary on his
review copy, fill out the appropriate portions of the traveller accompanying his copy,
and return the copy with its traveller to the writer by the deadline shown on the
traveller.
.skip 1
.paragraph
     Each reviewer of a document is responsible for returning his copy of the
document with its filled-out traveller to the writer by the date shown on the
traveller. If a reviewer cannot meet the deadline for a valid reason, he must so
inform the writer. Otherwise, failure to return a document by the deadline shown on
the traveller signifies the reviewer's approval of the document as is.
.skip 2
1.3  QUALITY SSURANCE TECHNICAL WRITER (WRITER)
.skip 1
.paragraph
     If the writer generates a document, he is responsible for collecting all
source data from every reliable source. Besides preparing the document
in accordance with sections 2 and 3 of this guide, he verifies all information in a
document for technical accuracy and completeness of coverage by discussion or
review with appropriate personnel.
.skip 1
.paragraph
     The writer is resposible for choosing the best format for documenting. The
normal formats are Reference Manuals, User Guides, and Quick References. These are
discussed in greater detail and illustrated in section 2. He is also responsible
for maintaining a document information file on the system. This
file is described in the *6NEWS file.
.skip 1
.paragraph
     If the writer accepts a document for editing and production  that was generated
by someone else, he observes the guidelines established in this guide.
.skip 1
.paragraph
     If a document is subject to formal review and approval, the writer is responsible
for monitoring the review and for obtaining approval as described in paragraph 2.5.3.
.skip 1
.paragraph
     Except in very rare cases, all documents are edited by the writer before they
are published. Editing is in accordance with guidelines provided in 
 sections 2 and 3 of this guide. Standard editorial marks are used. (See
appendix A).
.skip 1
.paragraph
     The writer uses illustrations to present material wherever they
would be the best, most practical means of communicating the meaning. He either 
obtains the services of the Publication Services Group in the Marketing
Division, or uses the services of an outside illustrator, or produces illustrations
himself as described in paragraph 4.2.3.
.skip 1
.skip 1
1.4  SECRETARY
.skip 1
1.4.1  ^&Typing Responsibilities\&
.skip 1
.paragraph
     The secretary is responsible for typing assignments handed her by the writer.
All typing will comply with the guidelines provided in sections 2 and 3 of this
guide. Secretaries will not edit text, but will type material exactly as it is 
submitted to them. If they should have questions about punctuation, wording or
formatting, they are responsible for asking the writer  - not the programmer - 
to resolve them before continuing with the typing.
.skip 1
.paragraph
     Before begin ning a job, check for instructions from the writer that would 
appear on the inside front cover of the folder containing the material to be
typed.
.skip 1
1.4.2  ^&Related Responsibilities\&
.skip 1
.paragraph
     Unless a document is to be printed by an outside vendor, the secretary is
responsible for reproducing documents on one of the Xerox machines at Tymshare,
in accordance with guidelines given to her by the writer.
.skip 1
.paragraph
     The secretary is also responsible for distributing copies and masters of
documents as described in paragraph 2.5.8 of this guide.
.skip 2
1.5  QUALITY ASSURANCE ANALYST
.skip 1
.paragraph
     For software items, the Quality Assurance Analyst who reviewed or cleared
the software being documented will also be responsible for reviewing the corresponding
document in draft form. The analyst should make any changes necessary on his
review copy, fill out the appropriate portions of the traveller accompanying his
copy, and return the copy with its traveller to the writer by the deadline shown on the
traveller.
.skip 1
.paragraph
     If an analyst does not return his copy of the document to the writer by the
deadline shown on his copy's traveller, such action signifies the analyst's approval
 of the document as is, unless the analyst informs the writer that he cannot
meet the deadline for a valid reason.
.skip 2
1.6  GROUP MANAGER
.skip 1
.paragraph
     Each group manager is responsible for reviewing and approving any document 
sent to him for review and approval. The manager should make any changes necessary on
his  review copy, fill out appropriate portions of the traveller accompanying the
copy, and return the copy with its traveller to the writer by deadline shown on the
traveller.
.paragraph
     If a manager does not return his copy of the document to the writer by the
deadline shown on the copy's traveller, such action will signify the manager's 
approval of the document as is, unless the manager informs the writer that he cannot
 meet the deadline for a valid reason.
